equation_narrative.headline: Buried hydrophobic core context drives confident leucine prediction through structural attention
equation_narrative.story: Position 50 sits in ubiquitin's hydrophobic core with 6 structural contacts. The model assembles this context through layers 1-23, reading predominantly hydrophobic neighbors (I, V, L) via structural attention. The representation remains hydrophobic-leaning throughout perception, with the logit lens fluctuating among branched aliphatics (I, V, L) as different structural features activate. At layer 25, the decision phase begins: leucine-specific prediction channels emerge, and by layer 29, L surges from 8% to 90% as MLP neurons cast decisive votes. The final 98% confidence reflects the model's certainty about the hydrophobic core environment.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 assemble a hydrophobic core context through structural attention. With 6 structural contacts and no co-evolutionary signal, the model focuses on local 3D chemistry. Early features (F1:5480, F1:9146, both 45+ proj) encode position identity and local sequence. By layer 9, structural reading intensifies (F9:5728, 47.5 proj) as the model integrates information from nearby hydrophobic residues. The logit lens fluctuates among branched aliphatics—I peaks at 29% (L6), V reaches 21% (L22), L oscillates between 8-20%—reflecting the representation's evolving hydrophobic character rather than prediction attempts. Mid-layer features (F18:2075, F18:6632) encode burial and core-packing preferences. The representation remains consistently hydrophobic-leaning, with polar/charged residues never exceeding 10% in the logit lens.
perception_phase.context_character: Buried hydrophobic core environment with 6 structural contacts, no co-evolutionary constraints. The representation encodes a tightly packed aliphatic environment consistent with leucine, isoleucine, or valine occupancy.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 6 residues within 8Å, predominantly hydrophobic (local sequence shows FAGKQ[L]EDGRT with hydrophobic neighbors)
No co-evolutionary signal: 0 coupled positions detected, indicating local structural packing dominates
L9 structural features: F9:5728 (attn, 47.5 proj) and F9:1281 (attn, 43.9 proj) encode hydrophobic core context
L18 burial encoding: F18:2075 (attn, 22.0 proj) and F18:6632 (attn, 19.4 proj) represent buried position character

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes between layers 25-29. At L25, leucine takes the lead at 20% as threonine (the previous leader at 35%) collapses. Layer 26 brings strong MLP support (N26:859 contributes 1.34 to L), pushing leucine to 39%. The decisive surge occurs at L27-29: MLP neurons N27:4723 (0.88 proj) and N29:431 (0.39 proj) drive L from 39% to 90%. By L30, leucine-specific prediction channels dominate (F30:4107 with 47.1 proj, F30:6887 with 37.0 proj), and the final layers refine to 98% confidence.
decision_phase.transition: The L23-25 boundary marks the perception-to-decision shift. At L23, the representation still encodes general hydrophobic character (V at 21%, T at 26%, L at 8%). At L24, amino-acid-specific prediction features first appear, though the representation remains uncertain. By L25, leucine-specific MLP neurons activate decisively, and the model commits to L as the answer rather than continuing to characterize the context.

candidates.narrative: Leucine emerges as the winner through decisive MLP voting in layers 26-29. N26:859 (1.34 proj) initiates the surge, followed by N27:4723 (0.88 proj) and sustained support from N28:101 (0.70 proj) and N30:2914 (1.00 proj). These neurons recognize the buried hydrophobic core signature and vote specifically for leucine over other branched aliphatics. By L30, leucine-specific attention features (F30:4107 at 47.1 proj, F30:6887 at 37.0 proj) lock in the prediction. The probability trajectory—8% at L23, 20% at L25, 90% at L29, 98% final—reflects the model's growing certainty as decision-phase evidence accumulates.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges at L25, surges L27-29, dominant by L30
key_evidence: N26:859 (1.34 proj to L) — strongest single MLP vote, initiates the leucine surge
F30:4107 (attn, 47.1 proj) — leucine-specific prediction channel in late attention
N30:2914 (1.00 proj to L) — sustained MLP support through final decision layers
Layer 29 velocity: +3.64 total delta driven by MLP (+5.10), pushing L from 63% to 90%

candidates.narrative: Valine dominates the logit lens through the perception phase, peaking at 21% at layer 22. This reflects the representation's compatibility with small branched hydrophobic residues during context assembly, not a model prediction. V's prominence arises because early structural features encode general β-branched aliphatic character—both L and V share this property. As the decision phase begins (L24+), valine collapses rapidly (10% at L23, 0.4% at L29) as leucine-specific neurons distinguish L's longer sidechain as the better fit for this particular packing geometry.
candidates.key_layers: Prominent L13-23, peaks at L22 (21%), collapses L24+
key_evidence: Logit lens peaks at 21.3% (L22) during perception phase, reflecting β-branched hydrophobic representation
Rapid collapse in decision phase: 10.2% (L23) → 0.4% (L29) as L-specific features activate
No dedicated V-specific MLP support in L24+ — representation character, not prediction

candidates.narrative: Isoleucine peaks early at 29% (L6) when the representation first encodes hydrophobic core character. Like valine, I's early prominence reflects the logit lens projecting a general aliphatic representation, not a model belief. The model is reading structural contacts and assembling a 'buried branched hydrophobic' representation that happens to correlate with isoleucine in the unembedding space. I declines steadily through perception (14% at L8, 8% at L17, 6% at L23) and collapses in the decision phase (1% at L29) as leucine-specific evidence accumulates.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks at L6 (29%), declines through perception, eliminated by L29
key_evidence: Early peak at 28.7% (L6) reflects initial hydrophobic core representation assembly
No MLP support in decision phase — early logit lens artifact, not a genuine candidate

candidates.narrative: Threonine briefly leads at layers 21-23, peaking at 26% (L23), despite being chemically incompatible with the hydrophobic core. This anomalous spike likely reflects mid-layer features that encode β-branched character (T shares this with V, I, L) without yet incorporating burial/hydrophobicity constraints. The decision phase immediately corrects this: T collapses from 26% (L23) to 3% (L25) as hydrophobicity-aware MLP neurons activate. Strong negative MLP votes (N25:4164 at -0.74 proj, N24:1790 at -0.43 proj) actively suppress threonine, recognizing its polar hydroxyl as incompatible with the buried environment.
candidates.key_layers: Briefly leads L21-23 (peaks 26%), immediately suppressed L24-25
key_evidence: Anomalous peak at 25.5% (L23) — likely β-branched encoding without hydrophobicity constraint
N25:4164 (−0.74 proj) and N24:1790 (−0.43 proj) actively erase T in decision phase
Rapid collapse: 25.5% (L23) → 3.3% (L25) as burial constraints activate

candidates.narrative: Methionine emerges as the only viable alternative to leucine in the decision phase, peaking at 20% (L26) before settling at 0.9% final. M receives genuine MLP support (N26:4894 at 0.55 proj votes for M over L, N28:101 at 0.95 proj for M) because methionine shares leucine's long hydrophobic sidechain and burial preference. However, M-specific neurons are outvoted 7:1 by L-specific neurons in layers 26-30. The model correctly distinguishes that this position favors the branched leucine over the linear methionine for optimal core packing.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges L24, peaks L26 (20%), fades L27-29
key_evidence: N26:4894 (0.55 proj to M) — recognizes long hydrophobic sidechain compatibility
N28:101 (0.95 proj to M, 0.70 to L) — genuine competition between M and L
Outvoted by L-specific neurons: total MLP proj L26-30 is +7.2 for L vs −0.1 for M

turning_points.description: The representation shifts from reading local sequence to integrating structural geometry. Attention heads begin structural reading (L17 head 1 contributes 1.44 proj without clear local source), and the logit lens fluctuates among branched aliphatics (V, L, I) as different packing features activate. The representation becomes more specific about burial: F18:2075 (22.0 proj) and F18:6632 (19.4 proj) encode core-packing preferences. This is still perception—the model is characterizing 'what kind of position is this' rather than 'what amino acid should go here.'

The perception-to-decision transition occurs here. At L23, the representation encodes general hydrophobic character with threonine anomalously leading (26%) due to β-branched features. At L24, amino-acid-specific prediction features first appear, though uncertainty remains high. At L25, leucine-specific MLP neurons activate decisively (N25:1108 at 0.55 proj, N25:1424 at 0.45 proj), and L takes the lead at 20%. Simultaneously, threonine-erasing neurons (N25:4164 at −0.74 proj) suppress the incompatible polar candidate. The model has shifted from 'this is a buried hydrophobic position' to 'this position should be leucine.'

The decisive surge: leucine probability jumps from 39% (L26) to 90% (L29). Layer 27 MLP contributes +7.18 via N27:4723 (0.88 proj), overcoming negative attention (−3.10). Layer 29 adds +5.10 MLP via N29:431 (0.39 proj) and N29:437 (0.36 proj). These neurons recognize the specific packing geometry that distinguishes leucine from other hydrophobic residues. Competing candidates collapse: M drops from 20% to 7%, V from 10% to 0.4%. The velocity events show MLP-driven acceleration toward the final answer.

deep_dives.label: Structural attention L1-18
deep_dives.caption: Early attention heads read the 6 structural contacts to assemble hydrophobic core context. Look for heads with high structural_attn values and positive projections—these are importing chemistry from 3D neighbors.

deep_dives.label: Perception features L9-18
deep_dives.caption: F9:5728 and F9:1281 encode hydrophobic core context from structural reading. F18:2075 and F18:6632 represent burial and packing geometry. These features characterize the position's environment, not predict the amino acid.

deep_dives.label: Logit lens L1-23 (perception)
deep_dives.caption: Watch I, V, L fluctuate as the representation assembles. These are NOT predictions—they reflect which amino acids correlate with the evolving hydrophobic representation in the unembedding space. The model is building context, not guessing.

deep_dives.label: Decision onset L23-25
deep_dives.caption: L23 shows general hydrophobic character (T at 26% is an artifact). L24-25 show the first leucine-specific MLP votes (N25:1108, N25:1424) and active threonine suppression (N25:4164). This is where perception becomes decision.

deep_dives.label: MLP surge L26-30
deep_dives.caption: The decisive votes: N26:859 (1.34), N27:4723 (0.88), N30:2914 (1.00) drive leucine from 20% to 95%. These neurons recognize the specific packing geometry that requires leucine over other hydrophobic residues. Note M receives some support (N26:4894, N28:101) but is outvoted.

deep_dives.label: Prediction channels L30-33
deep_dives.caption: F30:4107 (47.1 proj) and F30:6887 (37.0 proj) are leucine-specific prediction channels that lock in the answer. F33:6423 (111.7 proj) and F33:4166 (109.6 proj) represent the final high-confidence leucine prediction. These are decision-phase features with high amino-acid specificity.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts leucine with 98% confidence by assembling a buried hydrophobic core context through structural attention (6 contacts, no co-evolution) and then activating leucine-specific prediction channels in layers 26-30. The strongest evidence comes from MLP neurons that recognize the specific packing geometry: N26:859 (1.34 proj), N27:4723 (0.88 proj), and N30:2914 (1.00 proj) collectively distinguish leucine's branched sidechain as optimal for this environment. The decision phase correctly resolves early ambiguity among branched aliphatics (I, V, L) and suppresses incompatible candidates (T, polar residues), demonstrating the model's ability to integrate 3D structural context into precise amino acid prediction.
